Very approximate analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Two-spacecraft bulk measurement of the CME taking into account the brightest portions of the CME bulk as the leading edge became untraceable about midway into the CME propagation through LASCO coronagraph imagery.

Initial plane-of-sky measurement made with running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3 using SWPC_CAT. Measurement was updated to have a 3D longitude of E90, as source seems to be on/along the East limb, and fits between E85 and E105 were achieved.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

Measurement based on approximate location of source as observed in UV imagery and based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 frames. This CME was not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to overnight data gap which lasted from 2024-12-03T12:23Z to 2024-12-04T00:38Z.

Measurement based on approximate location of source as observed in UV imagery and based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 frames. This CME was not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to overnight data gap which lasted from 2024-12-03T12:23Z to 2024-12-04T00:38Z.

Measurement of faint leading edge using C2 and COR2A. This CME was not visible in C3 difference imagery; it was nearly entirely blocked by the pylon and the partial edge that could be seen was extremely faint and unreliable to track. The leading edge is faint and quickly becomes diffuse in both C2 and COR2A.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Two spacecraft measurement using triangulation to determine longitude.
Bulk measurement as the leading edge becomes diffuse with time, utilizing both SOHO and STEREO A for triangulation.

Preliminary leading edge measurement using one spacecraft (SOHO) which considers a large latitude to fit visual observations; uncertainty in longitude is quite large and may be as large as +/- 30 degrees.
Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Parameters based on best fit between SOHO and STEREO A difference imagery.

Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs.

Best fit measurement using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2; fits very well to source location (~S10W50) observed in UV imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery in SWPC_CAT. The CME is partially obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The leading edge becomes too diffuse to measure after a few frames, and the measured parameters rely on early imagery as a result.

Analysis based on the best fit with 2 coronagraphs, somewhat contradicting the location of the flare (long ~-77 deg). Analysis is complicated by a large data gap in SOHO, as well as by the partial obscuring of this CME by SOHO C3 pylon. Longitude of the CME could be as high as -70 degrees (with a different fit with 2 coronagraphs in the tool)
Analysis based on the best fit in two coronagraphs and confirmed by the location of the associated flare.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs and confirmed by location of the flare.
Very approximate analysis based on the fit in two coronagraphs and later confirmed by the possible source (continuous activity all morning culminating with 08Z dimming in AR 3920).
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. It differs a bit from the location of the associated flare, so there is some westward deflection, in addition to significant southward deflection.

Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and one frame in STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is high uncertainty due to lack of clear source and having only one frame in STEREO A COR2 imagery of this CME.

This analysis is based off of the best fit using SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. The front becomes too diffuse/faint to track before it exits the C2 field of view. It is not clearly seen in SOHO LASCO C3 difference imagery.

These parameters are based on the potential source location (accounting for deflection of source to the NE) and the best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 difference imagery. The front has a diffuse front making for tricky analysis.

These parameters are based on the potential source location (accounting for deflection of source to the NE) and the best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 difference imagery. The front is pretty diffuse in SOHO LASCO C2 difference imagery but becomes slightly more clear in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery, however there are overlapping features making this analysis a bit uncertain.
This CME deflects far to the south with continued deflection southward as it progresses through the SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 field of view. Due to this, there is some uncertainty with the fit.
Parameters based off of the best fit in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 using the potential source location for longitude and adjusting the latitude to fit the CME.
Based on the fit with two coronagraphs, which confirms the source location as the location of the likely associated Active Region 3920 which is showing some minor activity.

Two spacecraft leading edge measurement using triangulation with difficulty seeing the CME leading edge in SOHO LASCO C2 due to an obscuring CME in front of the CME in question; GONG data supports the eruption coming from a far-sided source with this approximate longitude.
Analysis based on the best fit in two coronagraphs but confirmed by source location (taking into account southward deflection).
Analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs, confirmed by the location of the associated flare.
One-spacecraft measurement attempting to fit both the south/south-southeast bulk measurement as well as the northeast portion in the SOHO LASCO C2 coronagraph.
Shock front measurement using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 incorporating the southeastward leading edge and western/eastern leading edges simultaneously in one circular-shaped measurement.
Bulk measurement using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 mainly focusing on brighter south portion of the CME.
Two spacecraft bulk measurement capturing the main shape of the CME inside of the protruding feature (i.e. the CME could be faster than this measurement).
One spacecraft measurement of the leading edge, holding the known longitude constant.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and limited STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Reanalysis of this event in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A going more northern and less wide, noting difficulty in tracking the same faint front between both coronagraphs on top of limited STEREO COR2A availaibility.

Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 as well as source location in SWPC_CAT. Only one frame of STEREO A COR2 was available for a measurement, and the majority of the measurement uses SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
Measurement based on source location and the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 in SWPC_CAT.
Preliminary one spacecraft measurement assuming that the eruption originates from the far-side.

Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. CME starts smaller than a 10 HW, expanding wider further into the FOV, and is notably deflected southward from the source region as corroborated in GOES SUVI.
Analysis with one coronagraph (SOHO) based on the location of the source (ejecta from former Active Region 3916).

Very uncertain analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs and giving preference to the minor eruption in AR 3916 as the source. However, the fit with the longitude of AR 3916 doesn't work, so there seems to be a deflection.

A very approximate/uncertain analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2) and since the longitude of the source eruption does not produce a good fit. The range of possible longitudes and latitudes is very high, with longitudes ranging from 30 to 50 deg.
Analysis  based on the best fit in two coronagraphs.
Approximate analysis based on a fit with two coronagraphs, but the front is fuzzy especially in STEREO A.
Approximate analysis based on the fit in two coronagraphs and on the location of the source (erupting filament).
Analysis based on the best fit in two coronagraphs and confirmed by one possible source (in STEREO EUV imagery).
Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery and potential source location.

Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in STEREO A COR2. Measurements with similar parameters using possible front seen in SOHO LASCO C3 were also made, but with lower confidence.
Parameters based on best fit of features in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME has a messy front so some uncertainty may be present with parameters.

Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery.

Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is some uncertainty about the measurement and triangulation of this CME because it is very faint in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 imagery and one frame of STEREO A COR2 imagery. Due to an ongoing STEREO A campaign limiting the amount of usable imagery, and the far-sided source, the measured parameters may vary slightly.

Leading edge measurement of the CME out to 18 solar radii using SOHO LASCO C3 and knowledge of the source location using EUV imagery.

Very uncertain analysis of the faint wider front (not the brighter narrow one), based on the fit of faint fronts in two coronagraphs and on the assumption that the source is Active Region 3938.

Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A, noting the CME is much fainter in COR2A running difference than COR2A white light. A very uncertain one-coronagraph (SOHO) analysis based on the assumption that the source is the eruption in Active Region 3939.
Leading edge measurement using SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2 to triangulate the source, which suggests higher confidence in the northern hemispheric eruption as opposed to AR 3939 in the southeast.

Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. This front appears to be slightly less than a halfwidth of 10, and also triangulated slightly further on-disk than the source observed in GOES SUVI imagery.

Single spacecraft (SOHO LASCO C2/C3) 3D measurement using the source location and faint observed deflection to the NW to get a good fit of this narrow, diffuse front which fades early in C3 in addition to traveling into the C3 pylon.

Single spacecraft (SOHO LASCO C2/C3) 3D measurement using the source location to get a fit of this wide, diffuse front, with notable difficulty due to the lack of STEREO COR2A imagery to triangulate a more accurate latitude/longitude to the slow eruption observed in SDO imagery.
One-coronagraph analysis based on the location of the source (filament eruption).
Very approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. The source is backsided and the front of the CME is not clear/fuzzy.
Very approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs.
Analysis based solely on the fit with two coronagraphs.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs.
Leading edge measurement using SOHO C2/C3 and knowledge of the source location of the eruption.
Leading edge measurement, confirming far-sided analysis.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A finding a good far-sided fit.

Triangulated measurment between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A, with good confidence in a matched far-sided fit around W120-W130 despite the lack of source observation in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI, or STEREO A EUVI. The brighter bulk of the front in SOHO imagery is notably dimpled inwards, but the outer edges were sharp enough to track the leading edge.
Leading edge measurement mainly relying on STEREO A but also using some late SOHO C3 frames; a poor confidence measurement of the velocity.
Measurement using late SOHO C3 frames during a SOHO C2/C3 data gap occurring during early portions of the CME.
Bulk measurement assuming modest deflection southward out of the ecliptic, though a discernible faint shock feature was associated with this event which seemed to be much wider and slower.
BULK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2
SHOCK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This shock feature was not visible in STEREO A COR2
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A.
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME appears to speed up in later frames.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A.

Best fit measurement using the source location visible on the Earth-facing disk in UV imagery and using several frames of both SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Data gap in STEREO A COR2 begins at 2025-01-22T12:53Z, so only the first few frames of the leading edge are captured in COR2.
SHOCK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Single spacecraft measurement with SOHO LASCO C2 as it fades in the FOV, using the source location of the M2.7 from AR 13961 at S05W70 with some northward deflection.
Single spacecraft measurement with SOHO LASCO C2 as it fades in the FOV, using the source location of AR 13961 at S10W60.

Measurement based on best fit between coronagraphs and location of the candidate source with southern deflection visible in UV imagery. The leading edge of this CME appears very diffuse in STEREO A COR2 imagery and becomes too diffuse to track after only a few frames. The leading edge remains visible for longer in SOHO LASCO, about halfway through the C3 field of view.
Parameters based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement using source location and best fit in only SOHO LASCO C3. Not captured in STEREO A COR2 in real time; data gap in STEREO A COR2 starting at 2025-01-25T18:23Z.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A. Only uses later frames of SOHO LASCO C3 due to acceleration from earlier C3 frames and C2.

SHOCK measurement of the faint, shock-like feature extending much wider than the brighter bulk, best observed in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. Only two usable frames of STEREO COR2A are available to triangulate this feature, and its longitude could range E40-E60 around the eruption source at E51.
BULK measurement of the brighter, inner feature of this CME. Triangulates well between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A imagery near the observed source centered around S20E51.
Analysis based on the fits with two coronagraphs and confirmed by the location of the source eruption.
One coronagraph analysis with SOHO LASCO imagery only, based on the clear location of the source eruption. There are no STEREO A coronagraph images available at this point because of the daily gap.

Measurement at W90 for the observed source in SDO AIA imagery, not a plane of sky. Triangulates between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A imagery, though notably faint and tought to discern in STEREO COR2A beacon running difference imagery.

Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. Due to poor visibility of this CME in STEREO COR2A running difference imagery, and the known source at W90 in SDO imagery, this longitude could slightly range W75-W95.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Due to the bizarre shape of this CME, especially in SOHO LASCO C2, this measurement was based on the furthest edge seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and more defined shape seen in SOHO LASCO C3
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2
Measurement using location of source observed in UV imagery and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Leading edge is very faint, especially in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Updated measurement based on the source location. Due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery at the time of this event, a triangulated measurement was not available and the measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.
Approximated longitude based on source location. Plausible longitude fits range from approx. W90 to W125.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2A. This event is not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 as it overlaps with CME: 2025-01-30T11:12Z.
BULK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2
SHOCK measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2

Measurement based on central location of filament eruption as seen in UV imagery, and best fit of shape in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 frames. CME not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-01-30T15:09Z.

Measurement based on location of opening field lines and brightest portion of post-eruptive arcades associated with an elongated filament eruption as seen in UV imagery, and best fit of shape in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 frames. This CME was not captured in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-01-30T15:09Z.

Preliminary measurement of the leading edge using only STEREO A data out to about 10 solar radii during a SOHO data outage. These parameters were later confirmed with the 2-Coronagraph measurement once SOHO became available.
Two spacecraft measurement of the leading edge; triangulation of the leading edge indicates some westward deflection occurred relative to the source region of the eruption.
Updated measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measurement of the bulk portion based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event has an irregularly-shaped leading edge, and the outermost feature was tracked in this measurement.
SHOCK measurement following the outermost, fainter shock feature based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the approximate source location, accounting for northeast deflection, and the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2.
BULK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2.
SHOCK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
BULK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
SHOCK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. As this event is far-sided and a precise source location is unknown, the measured parameters may vary slightly.
Measurement based on the approximate source location, accounting for visible southern deflection, and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
One coronagraph analysis (SOHO only) in the absence of STEREO A imagery.
Measurement using best fit between several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. Agrees with source location seen in UV imagery.
Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 difference imagery. The leading edge becomes diffuse about halfway through the STEREO A COR2 field of view.
Best fit measurement using running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
One spacecraft leading edge measurement by approximating the latitude.
Best fit measurement based on running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 and on the location of the erupting filament.
Leading edge of the fainter shock-like portion of this CME which accelerates away from the brighter bulk using only SOHO LASCO C2.
Leading edge measurement using two spacecraft to triangulate the longitude.

SHOCK measurement using only SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, as STEREO COR2A beacon running difference imagery does not resolve this front after it resumes from a data gap at 2025-02-06T05:09Z, making triangulation within swpc_cat not possible with real-time imagery. Via visual fitting of this wide shock front, a range of E140-E155 is likely, as further longitudes in either direction make for a poor visual fit of the shock.

BULK measurement using only SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery, as STEREO COR2A beacon running difference imagery does not resolve this front after it resumes from a data gap at 2025-02-06T05:09Z, making triangulation within swpc_cat not possible with real-time imagery. This measurement includes all lobes of the more dense bulk following the shock.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2. Front fades before exiting the field-of-view in SOHO LASCO C2.
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2

Stereoscopic best-fit measurement taken after STEREO A COR2 data gap ended. The data gap lasted from 2025-02-07T15:38Z to 2025-02-08T02:53Z. The leading edge is very faintly visible for one frame of STEREO A imagery before becoming too diffuse to discern, but fortunately, the leading edge in that one frame is clear enough to achieve a best-fit measurement between STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
Measurement based on potential source location. This measurement is approximate, and based on a few frames of SOHO LASCO C2.
Measurement based on source location. The CME was not measurable in SOHO LASCO C3.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery in SWPC_CAT and the potential source location as viewed from STEREO A EUV imagery.

Two-coronagraph analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs once STEREO A imagery became available. The longitude of the fit is confirmed by the location of the erupting filament (on or close to the east limb).
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. No source have been found for this event, so it is likely farsided.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measured longitude based on the approximate source location. Due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 at the time of this event, a triangulated measurement was not possible. The measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.
Measurement using SOHO LASCO C2 frames and source location. Leading edge becomes diffuse before leaving the SOHO LASCO C2 field of view.
Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery as well as the location of the source seen in UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk.

SHOCK measurement of a faint feature traveling ahead and slightly faster than the brighter bulk feature. Triangulated measurement with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A imagery, finding a good fit at E90, not as a plane-of-sky.

BULK measurement of the bright feature traveling slightly slower than the faint shock feature. Triangulated measurement with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A imagery, finding a good fit at E90, not as a plane-of-sky.
Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2

These parameters are based on the best fit of features in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is likely deflection of this CME due to the large coronal hole south of the potential source location.
Preliminary one spacecraft leading edge measurement of the CME assuming that the source on the Earth-facing disk best represents this CME.
Two spacecraft leading-edge measurement using SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 to corroborate the longitude.
Two spacecraft leading edge measurement.
Single spacecraft 3D measurement using only SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery due to a STEREO COR2A data gap covering this CME, using the source coordinates of N14E33 as a basis.
Single spacecraft 3D measurement using only SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery due to a STEREO COR2A data gap covering this CME, using the source coordinates of S30E68 as a basis.

A very speculative measurement based on the possible but not clear source and on a very approximate fit with two coronagraph. The fit is uncertain since especially in STEREO A the front of this CME is super unclear.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs; it corresponds well to the location of the source eruption.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs and corresponding well to the southern filament see in EUVI imagery.
Measurement based on approximate source location. Only SOHO LASCO C2 imagery was available for a measurement, as the CME was blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3.

Best fit measurement using several SOHO LASCO C3 frames and two frames of STEREO A COR2 before the leading edge leaves the COR2 field of view. This CME is partially covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which lasted from 2025-02-15T16:53Z to 2025-02-16T05:23Z.
Best fit measurement using SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2, as well as the source location seen in UV imagery. Leading edge is too diffuse to track in SOHO LASCO C3.
Best fit measurement using an abundance of SOHO LASCO C2 frames, two frames of C3, and two frames of STEREO A COR2. The leading edge becomes diffuse after a few frames of C3 and of COR2.

Best fit measurement using candidate source location, several SOHO LASCO C2 frames, and two frames of SOHO LASCO C3. The leading edge is narrow and for most frames is completely obstructed by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is completely covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which lasted from 2025-02-16T11:38Z to 2025-02-16T15:23Z.

Measurement based on source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2. Latitude matches well, but longitude is measuring slightly east of source location; there may have been deflection due to the nearby coronal hole observed in UV imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measured longitude based on the source location. As this event is not easily observed in STEREO A COR2 imagery, a triangulated measurement was not made and the measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Parameters based off of potential source location. Parameters may be off due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints.
Measurement of shock front using only SOHO C2/C3.

Bulk measurement encompassing more of the brighter, far-southern deflected piece of the CME using SOHO C2/C3 and assuming some moderate westward deflection based on EUV signatures (i.e. about 10-15 degrees from the source).
Measurement of the leading edge using two spacecraft.
Triangulation of the leading edge using SOHO and STEREO A, which measures slightly farther east than was anticipated given the source location of the eruption.
Two spacecraft leading edge measurement using SOHO/STEREO A to triangulate the approximate longitude.
Leading edge measurement using all available imagery from two spacecraft out to approximately 18 solar radii.
Two spacecraft measurement of the leading edge using triangulation of the leading edge to determine the longitude.
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 as well as general location of the complex candidate source.
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 as well as location of the complex candidate source.
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 as well as the location of the source filament eruption as seen in available UV imagery of the disk.
Very approximate one-coronagraph (SOHO LASCO) coronagraph analysis based on the very approximate/uncertain source location (minor activity on/near the NW limb).
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs, in the absence of clear source.
One-coronagraph analysis (with SOHO LASCO), based on the location of the likely source (associated flare).
Leading edge/bulk measurement fit to the source using two spacecraft, despite STEREO A imagery being in a campaign and limiting available imagery.

Measurement of the leading edge using only SOHO C2/C3; inclusion of STEREO A COR2A data suggests the eruption originates from W55-65 but is not supported by EUV imagery. Uncertainty in longitude about 25 degrees.

One spacecraft measurement of the leading edge (SOHO), as triangulation of the leading edge with STEREO A seemed to suggest the source region was centered around W55-W65, which is not supported by EUV imagery.

Shock front measurement using only SOHO imagery, encompassing the entire width of the CME in support of solar energetic particle modeling efforts. WSA-Enlil+CONE simulations associated with this measurement are created in support of solar energetic particle modeling purposes and model outputs should not be used for CME trajectory analysis.

Bulk for trajectory analysis using only SOHO imagery focusing on mid-point of the leading edge in the northwest, the northern portion is faster than this measurement and eastern portion (portion representing the ecliptic plane) is slower than this measurement, due to the tilt of CME out of the ecliptic with respect to occulting disk.

BULK. Triangulated measurement of the brightest bulk portion of the leading edge, notably clipping some of the more faint nose off the northern portion in SOHO C3 imagery due to the uneven front. This analysis may be preliminary as further analysis continues.

Measurement based on running difference imagery from STEREO A COR2 and on-disk source location. There is significant uncertainty in this measurement due to the lack of measurable LASCO C2/C3 imagery. This CME is very difficult to distinguish from the previous CME is C2 and is obscured by the pylon in C3.

This is a SHOCK measurement. Parameters based on best fit adjusted from source location using single-spacecraft measurement method. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this event due to a data gap.

This is an updated BULK measurement with later frames. Parameters are based on the best fit of CME features based on potential source location using single-spacecraft measurement method. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this event due to a data gap.
Measurement based on source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2
Measurement based on approximate source location. CME is too faint to be reliably tracked and triangulated in STEREO A COR2.
Parameters based on best fit of brightest leading edge and bulk of CME.
Parameters based on best fit of features in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 difference imagery.
Parameters are based off of the best fit of the features in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measured longitude based on the source location. Due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery, a triangulated measurement was not available. The measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measurement using a very limited number of frames. Parameters based on candidate source location seen in STEREO A EUV imagery and best fit between two frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery. There is a data gap that begins in STEREO A COR2 at 2025-02-27T07:53Z and the leading edge is too diffuse to track after the gap ends at 2025-02-27T09:23Z. The leading edge becomes visible halfway through C2 field of view after the end of a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2, and once it enters the C3 field of view, it is almost entirely blocked by the pylon and cannot reliably be tracked.
Measurement based on source location as well as the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery in SWPC_CAT.
Measurement based on approximate source location using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery in SWPC_CAT. STEREO A COR2 imagery was not available for this measurement.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Parameters based on the best fit of the BULK of the CME. The leading edge has a slight dimpled shape in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Very approximate analysis of a faint wider shock mostly seen in coronagraph running difference imagery, which seems to be more farsided. This is also confirmed by the fact that the EUV wave is not seen on the Earth facing side in EUV imagery, but there are signatures of a far-sided EUV wave behind the limb, seen in AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284 imagery.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Leading edge measurement using two spacecraft indicating strong northern deflection (out of the ecliptic). Uncertainty in latitude about +/- 10 degrees, though the longitude is well confined.
Parameters based on best fit adjusted from source location with apparent deflection to the south taken into account.

Very preliminary measurement with limited frames in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. No STEREO A COR2 available due to data gap. The CME exhibits a sheered-type of front with a portion moving faster than other portions. These parameters are based on following the faster portion of the CME with including the slower portion within the width of the measurement. The slower portion of this CME was measuring speeds closer to 200 km/s.
Analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs. It's somewhat confirmed by the location of the flare (but there seems to be some deflection westward).
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs and confirmed by the location of the likely source (C class flare).
Analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs confirmed by the location of the most likely source - the associated flare.
Analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs. Faint coronal signatures also indicate that this is a far-sided CME.
3D measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2
Parameters based on best fit of faint front in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Parameters based on best fit of the CME using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Strong deflection is likely due to nearby coronal holes.
Parameters based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Updated measurement with more SOHO LASCO C3 frames now available. Based on the approximate source location.

Measured longitude based on the source location. Due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery at the time of this event, a triangulated measurement was not available and the measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.
A very approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. The front is very unclear/fuzzy in STEREO A COR2 and no source has been found for this event, so this analysis is very uncertain.

Measurement using the location of the source seen in UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk and the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. The full leading edge and a small interior flux rope are both faintly visible in C2, but this CME is only tentatively seen as an extremely faint feature for two frames in STEREO A COR2, so there is some uncertainty with this measurement. The best fit parameters match well with the approximated source location if taking into account some southern deflection, though, which increases confidence a bit. Leading edge is too diffuse to track in SOHO LASCO C3.

Triangulated measurement using mostly SOHO LASCO C2/C3 frames, with two STEREO COR2A frames helping triangulate the longitude prior to its data gap beginning at 2025-03-05T11:53Z. This CME front diffuses out after an initial solid view in LASCO C2, it was much easier to track the leading edge in the earliest frames used for this measurement.
Analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs. There seems to be a northward and eastward deflection from the location of the source eruption.

Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. Narrow leading edge is faint but well-defined in C2, distinguishable but not as well-defined in STEREO A COR2, and defined for only two frames in C3.

Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. Leading edge is too diffuse to reliably track in SOHO LASCO C3. This best-fit measurement corroborates the southward and westward deflection of this eruption from the source location as was suspected based on visual inspection of UV imagery.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

Measurement tracking the northernmost feature (as seen in SOHO LASCO C2), which seems to correspond to an extremely faint loop seen in late frames of STEREO A COR2. This feature in C2 appears to be traveling slightly faster than the surrounding/overlapping material, which becomes diffuse and seems to fall apart or loose momentum before reaching the edge of the C2 field of view. The northernmost feature reaches into the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

Measurement using best fit between the abundance of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 frames available. Source location with southern deflection observed in UV imagery was taken into consideration when conducting this measurement.

Best fit measurement using several frames of STEREO A COR2, four frames of SOHO LASCO C3, and two frames of SOHO LASCO C2. The leading edge is very faint in SOHO LASCO imagery; it is much more well-defined in STEREO A COR2. This CME visually overlaps with CME:2025-03-07T21:49Z in both SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2.
Leading edge of the southwest portion of the CME and not the leading edge seen more to the south in STEREO A COR2 later frames.
Leading edge measurement using only SOHO C2 as the CME is not seen well in STEREO A, possibly being edge on. This measurement assumes some modest deflection of a few degrees to the west.
Measured longitude based on the approximate source location.
Measurement based on the approximate source location, accounting for southeast deflection, and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs.
Measurement based on the source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the approximate source location, accounting for southern deflection, and the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measurement using source location seen in UV imagery and best fit between a few frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery. The leading edge is very faint in both coronagraphs and becomes too diffuse to reliably track about halfway through the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view.

Very approximate analysis as this jet was measured with the 10 deg halfwidth using the one-coronagraph method in swpc_cat, based only on SOHO imagery and on the location of the associated flare. While the jet is extremely narrow (<2 degrees half-width, lowest half-width setting in swpc_cat that we have to use is 10 degrees).
Leading edge measurement using triangulation from two spacecraft (SOHO, STEREO A) to determine a potential longitude; approximately a 20 degree uncertainty in longitude.
Leading edge measurement using only SOHO imagery and knowledge of the source eruption location to determine the longitude.
Analysis based solely on the fit with two coronagraphs.

Difficult to triangulate measurement between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A due to the faint, wispy nature of the leading edge. Good confidence in the high southern latitude and longitude around W50-W60.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO COR2A, using only the earliest frames as the CME fades into the running difference background by 2025-03-13T06:00Z.
One spacecraft measurement (SOHO) of the leading edge assuming some modest northern deflection and fitting relative to the source observed in EUV imagery.

Measurement of wider shock front using only SOHO C2 and knowledge of the source as determined from EUV imagery. Attached WSA-Enlil+Cone simulation was executed in support of SEP models and should not be used for CME trajectory analysis. Based on simulation output, there is low confidence the CME may arrive at Earth very weakly.
Two spacecraft leading edge measurement in order to triangulate a possible longitude; uncertainty in longitude up to +/- 20 degrees.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2. This event is measuring slightly more narrow than the SWPC_CAT lower limit of 10 degrees.
Approximate analysis based solely on the fit with two coronagraphs.

Measurement made using the best fit between abundant frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery, as well as consideration of the source location seen in available STEREO A EUV, SDO AIA, and GOES SUVI imagery.

Measurement made using the best fit between abundant frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery, as well as consideration of the source location seen in available STEREO A EUV, SDO AIA, and GOES SUVI imagery.

Uncertain analysis based solely on the best possible fit with two coronagraphs. The high posts-eruptive arcades behind the west limb in STEREO A EUV imagery showing much later than the original coronal signatures of opening field lines indicate the source with the longitude >120 deg. However, no fit was found with longitudes >115 deg and the best fit was obtained with the longitude of 109 degrees. Likely deflection of about 10 to 20 degrees eastward relative to the source at W125 would be caused by a large coronal hole located to the northwest of Active Region 4012 at approximately W125.
A very uncertain analysis based on the fit of the very faint fuzzy front in both coronagraphs. No source has been found.
One-coronagraph analysis with corrected latitude of the CME (~25 degrees). Analysis is based on SOHO imagery and on the location of the likely source - faint eruption centered around (N25W10).

Measurement of the leading edge/bulk using two spacecraft out to 8 solar radii which supports westward deflection. Triangulation does not support the source location being near the original source location N35E35. Not yet seen in SOHO C3.

Very low confidence two spacecraft measurement of very faint shock front, which is hardly seen in running difference imagery. Attached WSA-ENLIL+Cone simulation was executed in support of SEP models and should not be used for CME trajectory analysis, potentially representing an overestimate of potential impacts relative to observations.

Analysis made with later SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery, leaving C2 imagery out to account for clear acceleration of the CME (from <200 km/s to >400 km/s) in later imagery. Analysis is based on the best fit in two coronagraphs, as no clear source was found on disk.  Analysis incorporates a very faint left hand side boundary of this CME as seen in later COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 and a source candidate.

Approximate one-coronagraph analysis with SOHO imagery only since the CME is not in STEREO A COR2A imagery (where it would be near center disk from the perspective of STEREO A). Analysis is based on the assumption that the source of this CME is a small filament eruption centered around N12W30 which starts around 2025-03-17T10:36Z and is best seen in SDO AIA 304.
Very approximate analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs, C2 and COR2A imagery only. The CME is too faint in C3. No clear source has been found for this CME.
Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. No source was found for this CME.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3
Measurement based on approximate center of source dimming region and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2.
Measurement based on approximate center of source dimming region and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.

Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME appears wider in COR2A likely due to the angle of the filament that each spacecraft is viewing.
Parameters based on the best fit using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measurement using best fit between SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery, as well as the approximated location of the source seen in STEREO A EUV imagery. The quality and cadence of STEREO A COR2 imagery was affected during time of analysis due to a campaign scheduled to last from 2025-03-18 to 2025-03-24.

Updated measurement using the approximated source longitude of former Active Region 14018, which was estimated to be centered near west 100 degrees at the time of this event. The measured parameters may vary slightly due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measurement using best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 running difference and STEREO A COR2 difference imagery, as well as the approximated location of source seen in available UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk. The quality and cadence of STEREO A COR2 imagery was affected during time of analysis due to a campaign scheduled to last from 2025-03-18 to 2025-03-24.
Leading edge measurement using one spacecraft assuming the source is associated with an eruption just north of AR 4022.
StereoCAT measurement using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A due to unusable data quality of COR2A running difference imagery in the swpc_cat tool, due to an ongoing STEREO A campaign.
Parameters based on the SHOCK of the CME using SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. High uncertainty due to lack of stereoscopic viewpoints.

Parameters based on the BULK of the CME using SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. The front of the bulk is not clearly visible in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery due to the control arm. High uncertainty of parameters due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints.
Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C3 imagery and the potential source location. Some uncertainty due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints.
Very approximate analysis based on the best fit with two coronagraphs and affected by the poor quality of STEREO A coronagraph imagery because of the ongoing campaign. The source is on the far side.
Measurement based on the source location.
Measurement based on the source location.
Measured longitude based on the source location. The eruption exhibits northern deflection which may explain the latitude measuring higher than the on-disk source latitude.

SHOCK measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and the one available frame of this event seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery, due to an ongoing campaign. This event is likely far-sided and the source location is unknown. The measured parameters may vary as a result.

BULK measurement using the same longitude as what was measured in the shock measurement. The measured parameters may vary greatly as the bulk portion of this event is difficult to distinguish in STEREO A COR2 imagery. Additionally, this event is likely far-sided so there is no source location to confirm the measured parameters.

Triangulated SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A measurement via the STEREOCAT tool, as STEREO COR2A is currently in campaign mode and its running difference imagery in SWPC_CAT does not resolve the faint CME well.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2.

Measurement based on best fit between coronagraphs and source location seen in UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery lasting from 2025-03-25T13:42Z to 2025-03-25T17:30Z, and by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery which began at 2025-03-25T15:53Z.

Measurement made using the source location seen in UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk, three frames of STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery with timestamps 2025-03-25T15:23Z, 2025-03-25T15:38Z, and 2025-03-25T15:53Z, as well as one frame of SOHO LASCO C3 running difference imagery at timestamp 2025-03-25T17:54Z. The leading edge is extremely diffuse in SOHO LASCO C3, which introduces some uncertainty. The leading edge of the CME is more clearly defined in the three frames of STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO C3. | Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery lasting from 2025-03-25T13:42Z to 2025-03-25T17:30Z, reduced image quality of SOHO LASCO C3 frames for timestamps following 2025-03-25T17:30Z, and by the regular overnight data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery which began at 2025-03-25T15:53Z.
SHOCK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
BULK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.

Measurement using an approximation of the source location just beyond the southeast limb based on UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk and the same four frames of SOHO LASCO C2 used in the plane-of-sky measurement. There is a high degree of uncertainty with this measurement due to the lack of available imagery and the uncertainty of the exact source location.
Analysis based mostly on the best fit with two coronagraphs, taking into account the C3.9 flare northwest of AR 4043.
A super uncertain analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. Uncertainty stems from both fronts being super faint and from the source has not found in EUV imagery.
This analysis is based on the fit with two coronagraphs. No source has been found for this CME.
Analysis based only on the fit with two coronagraphs.
Updated measurement using later imagery based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

SHOCK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. This measurement contains a high degree of uncertainty due to the lack of available frames as a result of data gaps in both SOHO and STEREO A COR2.

Measurement of the bulk using several more frames of SOHO LASCO C3 imagery than previously available. There is still only one STEREO A COR2 frame available for this CME, but the fit found using C3 frames the source location aligns well with this one STEREO A COR2 frame.
Parameters are based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on source seen in UV imagery and best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.

A very tentative analysis based mostly on the SOHO LASCO imagery and on the location of the source (but to some degree confirmed by a couple timestamps in STEREO A COR2 imagery in which the front could possibly be seen very faintly after the data gap. The longitude of -85 degrees fits better than -80 degrees.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. It looks like there is significant southern deflection, since the associated flare is from south of Active Region 4048 that is at latitude of 16 degrees south.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs and confirmed by the location of the associated filament eruption (close to the NW limb).
Measured longitude based on the source location. The leading edge of this event becomes too diffuse to measure in later imagery, so this measurement relies on early frames.

Two spacecraft leading edge measurement using triangulation to determine the longitude of the source; the CME becomes very diffuse with time and is extremely difficult to see in STA COR2 past 8 solar radii.

Best fit measurement of faint leading edge using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2, C3 and STEREO A COR2. Strong eastern and southern deflection was visible from the source location seen in UV imagery of the Earth-facing disk, which is reflected in the best fit parameters.
Measurement using best fit between several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and two frames of STEREO A COR2.
Parameters based on best fit using SOHO imagery and possible source location longitude.

Measurement using best fit between several SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 frames. The leading edge becomes diffuse halfway through the STEREO A COR2 field of view.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A, tracking well with the far southern latitude dimming around S60W20 observed in SDO AIA 193.

Best fit measurement of leading edge using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. Strong northern deflection was visible from the source location seen in UV imagery from SDO AIA, STEREO A EUVI, and GOES SUVI, which is reflected in the best fit parameters.

Measurement of the faint leading edge, based on source location seen in STEREO A EUVI and fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-04T17:38Z. The leading edge becomes diffuse only a handful of frames into the SOHO LASCO C3 field of view.
Parameters based on best fit of features in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is some uncertainty due to lack of clear source in available EUV imagery.

Very approximate analysis of the main brightest front/loop, obtained by fitting with two coronagraphs. Based on the coronal signatures, the source is behind the east limb, but close enough to the limb for the tops of the post-eruptive arcades to start peaking from behind the limb two hours after the eruption.

A very approximate, speculative analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. The source is likely far behind the east limb and the front is not clear as the CME is largely overlapping with the earlier CME.
Analysis based solely on the fit with two coronagraphs, since the source is not completely clear and is likely behind the limb.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. The source is behind the northeast limb.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs. The source marked by post eruptive arcades seems to be just beyond the east limb.
Two spacecraft bulk measurement with high confidence in parameters, good fit relative to observed source location.
Shock measurement in SOHO and STEREO A by encompassing the faint northeast edge in both spacecraft as well as the bright bulk.
Leading edge measurement using two spacecraft to triangulate the longitude out to 14 solar radii.

Analysis based on the location of the source (filament eruption on disk) and confirmed by the fit in two coronagraphs. The longitude can vary a bit (+-5 degrees).

Measurement based on source location and using only C2 frames, since this CME has not yet reached the C3 field of view. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-09T18:53Z.

Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

Measurement based on source location and best fit using several frames of C2 and a few frames of C3. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-11T11:23Z.

Measurement based on source location and best fit in several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and C3. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-11T11:23Z.

Measurement using source location seen in UV imagery and several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and a few frames of C3. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-11T11:23Z.

Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery in SWPC_CAT as well as source location. The CME appears to speed up in later frames. The CME may deflect to the east of the potential source location.

Leading edge measurement using two spacecraft to triangulate a potential longitude; seen just beyond the northeastern limb in EUV imagery.

Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs, setting the half-width to the swpc_cat tool's minimum 10 degrees. The CME is very narrow (narrower than 10 degrees half-width) so the speed could have been underestimated in this analysis.

Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A.
Two spacecraft leading edge measurement, which determined the CME was likely far out of the ecliptic. Upper bound on half-width.

A very approximate analysis based on the fit in two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2). However, the front is so undefined/fuzzy except for 2 images (one in C2 and another in COR2A) that parameters are very uncertain. The source is likely far-sided.

A very uncertain analysis based on the assumption that activity in AR 4079 is the source of this CME and on the front in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 coronagraph. The CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A.

Very approximate analysis based on the likely source of this CME (minor filament eruption close to the southwest limb) and confirmed by the two coronagraph fit with the super faint front in STEREO A and with (a more easily traceable) front in SOHO LASCO C2.
Analysis based on the fit of the front with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2). There seems to be a northward deflection or rotation going on.
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2) and somewhat confirmed by the possible coronal signature - faint dimming north of the disk center.
Very approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2). The source is seen on/close to the NE limb.

Approximate analysis based on the fit of the faint fuzzy front in two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2) and confirmed by the likely source location (eruption in a minor unnumbered region).
Very approximate analysis (+-10 degrees), based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2), taking into account the likely source - a filament off the east limb.
Analysis based solely on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2).
Very uncertain analysis based solely on the fit of the left boundary of this fuzzy faint CME in two coronagraphs (STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO).
A super approximate analysis based on fitting the halo in SOHO LASCO coronagraph. The CME front is not seen in STEREO A coronagraph at all. The source is likely far-sided.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement base don best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

Two spacecraft measurement taking into account the faint and wide feature in STEREO Ahead out ahead of the brighter core portion in addition to the brightest portion of the bulk in SOHO C2/C3 which was required for triangulation to fit relative to the source of the eruption; assumes some eastward deflection due to a coronal hole located just northwest of the eruptive active region.
Two spacecraft measurement using SOHO and STEREO A with imagery that did not overlap due to an early SOHO data gap and relatively later STEREO A data gap; uncertainty in longitude about 15 degrees.

SOHO leading edge measurement out to 9 solar radii due to a STEREO A data gap; a SOHO plane of sky measurement with longitude 90 degrees west probably approximates to this eruption well to the nearest +/-5 degrees based on the filament eruption observed in SDO AIA/GOES SUVI 304.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This measurement relies on early imagery as this event is overtaken by CME: 2025-05-14T07:12Z after a few frames.

Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The measured parameters may vary slightly as the source is likely far-sided and a precise source location is unknown.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Only two frames of STEREO A COR2 are usable, so running difference image quality is low, but it is enough to track the front and triangulate.
Measurement based on the source location and the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and one frame of STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Triangulated measurement betweeen SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. The LASCO C3 pylon obscures CME visiblity in the running difference imagery and it cannot be resolved there.
Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There may be some uncertainty due to faintness of event.
Preliminary measurement based on source location and visible features in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery. Uncertainty with parameters due to limited available frames and faintness of event.

This measurement is approximate due to lack of available triangulation. The only STEREO A COR2 frame in which this CME is visible is too faint to be usable for measurement. The source location is based on a visible on-disk source.
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2
Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 and on the visible source near the NE limb.
Measurement based on SOHO LASCO C2 only and on visible source location (AR 14090 S12E75). The frame in SOHO LASCO C3 in which this CME is visible is not clear enough to use in the measurement.

Very speculative analysis based on the fit of a very faint and uncertain front with two coronagraphs in one timestamp. There are very few images with the front of this CME seen in coronagraphs and its source is also very faint and speculative.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is not measurable in SOHO LASCO C3 as it is blocked by the pylon.
Approximate analysis using best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.
This analysis is based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2).
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO).
Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2).
A very speculative analysis of this very faint event  without a found source. Analysis is based on the fit of the very faint and incomplete front in two coronagraphs, SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME appears to speed up in later frames.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on the source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

Single spacecraft 3D measurement with SOHO LASCO C2 only. STEREO A COR2 not available due to a data gap, and the LASCO C3 pylon greatly obscures the CME front in white light and running difference imagery. As such, the latitude and longitude may vary +- 10 degrees in either direction, with good confidence in the southern deflection from the observed source via SDO AIA and GOES SUVI imagery.

Single spacecraft 3D measurement with SOHO LASCO C2 only, becoming notably more faint after several frames. STEREO A COR2 not available due to a data gap, and the LASCO C3 pylon greatly obscures the CME front in white light and running difference imagery. As such, the latitude and longitude may vary +- 10 degrees in either direction, with good confidence in the southern deflection from the observed source via SDO AIA and GOES SUVI imagery.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Because the source is far-sided, a precise source location is unknown and the measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.
Parameters based on best fit in relation to source location. Parameters may vary by +/- 10 degrees due to overlapping features in coronagraph imagery.
Measurement is speculative. Imagery in LASCO C2 is only available in early frames, and LASCO C3 is only available in later frames. Imagery from STEREO A COR2 is very grainy.
Best fit measurement based on triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 and visible source location on/near the NE limb.
Best fit based on triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 and visible source location.
Measurement based on the BULK of the CME. Parameters are based on best fit relying more heavily on STEREO A COR2 imagery to differentiate the bulk and shock features.

Measurement of faint SHOCK feature. Parameters based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. A portion of the shock front to the NW from SOHO LASCO C3's field-of-view was excluded from this fit due to measurement technique limitations.

Analysis based on the best fit of this narrow jet with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2) and confirmed by the location of the likely source (filament eruption). It looks like the CME is deflecting southward.

Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2) and supported by the range of possible longitudes (based on the CME appearing northeast in LASCO and northwest in STEREO A). This analysis is based on the clearer second front directly following a messier first front of the CME, as they appear in both coronagraphs.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.

Difficult triangulation with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, as STEREO A COR2 data quality and the diffuse front directed towards STEREO A made for tough visibility in running difference imagery. Triangulated north and west of the observed source region at S06W45, indicating some deflection.

Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. E90 is the triangulated longitude and this is not plane-of-sky. Due to the faint front and overlap with a concurrent streamer blowout, the earliest visible frames are omitted for a better tracking of the front.
Analysis based on the fit in two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2) and confirming the source as the filament eruption significantly east of Active Region 14098.

A highly speculative measurement based on the location of the flare and the front in SOHO LASCO C2, adjusted for what is possibly the faint front in STEREO A COR2. The front in COR2 is extremely faint and is difficult to ascertain and the analysis is hence speculative.
Very approximate analysis based exclusively on the best fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2), since no source has been found in EUV imagery.
Very approximate analysis based on the fit in two coronagraphs.
Analysis based on the location of the flare/eruption (AR 14100) and the best fit with two coronagraphs, SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2.
Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2).
SHOCK measurement of the more faint outer feature, triangulated between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
BULK measurement of brighter inner feature, triangulated between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on best fit between several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery.
Leading edge measurement encompassing the CME's path traversing the ecliptic plane as the CME pitch angle increases with time.
Leading edge measurement using SOHO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 for triangulation.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. This event is too faint to be reliably tracked in SOHO LASCO C3.
Measurement based on visible source location.
Measurement based on triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 and on visible source location in STEREO A EUVI.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. This event is not measurable in SOHO LASCO C3 as it is obscured by the pylon.
Preliminary analysis of the SHOCK using about four frames of GOES CCOR-1 and four frames of SOHO LASCO C3.
Analysis of the BULK using about four frames of GOES CCOR-1, four frames of SOHO LASCO C3, and two frames of STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is too faint to be reliably measured in SOHO LASCO C3.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in STEREO A COR2. This CME was not visible to measure in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
Measurement based on best fit in STEREO A COR2 and low confidence fit in GOES CCOR. This CME does not reliably appear in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.
Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs, as no clear source has been found.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery in SWPC_CAT.

Best fit measurement using multiple frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and two usable frames of STEREO A COR2. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which lasted from 2025-06-02T23:53Z to 2025-06-03T00:53Z, resulting in there being two usable frames before the tracked feature exited the STEREO A COR2 field of view.

Analysis of the first closed loop front (not the initial dimpled/broken/fuzzy front) based on the best fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2). This analysis is approximate, as longitude of the fit can vary from -17 to 27 degrees.

Approximate analysis based on the fit of this narrow CME in two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2). No source was found for this event, however it is worth noting that the CME latitude and longitude are just north of the recently opened coronal hole which was gradually 'opened' by a very slow motion eruption associated with the 2025-06-03T07:48Z CME.
Approximate analysis based on the fit of the fuzzy faint front in two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2).
Parameters based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The parameters may vary by +/- 10 degrees due to the faintness of the CME.
Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery.
Best fit measurement using triangulation between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 and source location seen in UV imagery of the disk. This CME was partially obstructed by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and one faint frame in STEREO A COR2 as well as visible source location over the NE limb.

Measurement based on triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 as well as visible source beyond the W limb. The couple of visible frames in COR2A help with triangulation, but the front itself is not defined enough to be used in the measurement.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Triangulated measurement between later frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 only, as the front fans out and widens, and deflects slightly northward, from its first visible frames in SOHO LASCO C2.

Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is notably less than 10 half width and deflects northward, making it difficult to track with the swpc_cat tool. High confidence in its high northern latitude.
Best fit using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and a few frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2, as well as source location seen in available UV imagery.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and STEREO A COR2 for two frames before the data gap begins at 2025-06-09T21:38Z. Measurement is at E90 and is not plane-of-sky.
Best fit using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and a few frames of STEREO A COR2, as well as source location seen in available UV imagery.
Measurement made using best triangulated fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. As the source is far-sided and a precise source location is unknown, the measured longitude may vary slightly.

Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The measured longitude may vary slightly as the source is far-sided and a precise source location is therefore unknown.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Triangulated measurement with SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. CME appears slightly less wide in STEREO A COR2 imagery, LASCO C3 measured half-width is used here.
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. CME appears to have deflected notably further north and west from the observed source near the limb (N16E90) via triangulation.

Triangulated measurement between later frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and two available, low quality running difference images of STEREO A COR2. The CME deflects northward as it travels through LASCO C2 to C3 so later frames capture the final width and direction better. STEREO A COR2 imagery becomes sparse over this CME leading to lower quality running difference imagery that is usable.
Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

Measured longitude based on the source location. A triangulated measurement was not available as this event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.
Measurement based on the best fit between GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME overlaps the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-06-11T14:36Z.
Parameters are based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The leading edge is slightly diffuse which may contribute to some uncertainty with these parameters.

Triangulated measurement using several frames of GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. About half of this CME is obstructed by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 which started at 2025-06-12T02:36Z and is scheduled to end at 2025-06-12T21:35Z.
Preliminary measurement. Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 imagery.

Triangulated measurement using several frames of GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. Analysis of this CME was affected by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 which started at 2025-06-12T02:36Z and is scheduled to end at 2025-06-12T21:35Z.

An extremely uncertain one-coronagraph (STEREO A COR2) analysis based on the location of the possible source of this CME, the filament eruption. The CME front of this CME is only seen in a few early timestamps of STEREO A COR2 coronagraph, superimposed on the previous CME. The CME is not seen in other coronagraphs.
Analysis based on the likely source of this CME (filament eruption in/near AR 14115) and confirmed by the good fit with two coronagraphs (STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3).
Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.
